00:09:48.320 --> 00:09:52.180 position:56%
detonated over Japan in August 1945,

00:09:52.180 --> 00:09:55.330
was observing that the
age was already passed,

00:09:55.330 --> 00:09:59.980
in which as he put it "Scientists
can disclaim responsibility

00:09:59.980 --> 00:10:03.570
for the use to which mankind
has put their discoveries."

00:10:03.570 --> 00:10:08.210 position:56%
And the reason he said was that what
big science had brought about was

00:10:08.210 --> 00:10:12.100
"Fraught with infinitely greater
dangers than all the inventions

00:10:12.100 --> 00:10:14.830
of the past put together."

00:10:14.830 --> 00:10:18.890 position:56%
And we need to talk not merely
about what we do with the knowledge.

00:10:18.890 --> 00:10:23.400
Big science brings us but the
resources we spend on that quest.

00:10:23.400 --> 00:10:26.690
Lawrence's legacy challenges
us to think about that.

00:10:26.690 --> 00:10:31.230
How to way the monumental effort,
it might take to put a man on Mars

00:10:31.230 --> 00:10:34.970
or discover the next fundamental
particle, against the imperative

00:10:34.970 --> 00:10:38.570
to fight cancer or pay for
drugs against hepatitis

00:10:38.570 --> 00:10:41.290
or multiple sclerosis
for every sufferer

00:10:41.290 --> 00:10:44.110
or to end poverty and hunger.

00:10:44.110 --> 00:10:47.830
So, all these I think fact is
into what makes Ernest Lawrence

00:10:47.830 --> 00:10:52.030
and his work such an
intriguing subject for us today.

00:10:52.030 --> 00:10:56.170
He was a small town boy,
born in 1901 in Canton,

00:10:56.170 --> 00:11:00.540
South Dakota to a first generation
Norwegian-American family.

00:11:00.540 --> 00:11:03.930
So it could be said that he
grew up with the 20th Century.

00:11:03.930 --> 00:11:07.810
Like many of his friends, he was
a thinker, fascinated in his case

00:11:07.810 --> 00:11:11.680
by radio gear and we could see the
qualities that made him a success

00:11:11.680 --> 00:11:14.040
in later life even in boyhood.

00:11:14.040 --> 00:11:16.370
Comfortable with technology
and machinery,

00:11:16.370 --> 00:11:20.710
I'm assuming curious
and bored with idleness.

00:11:20.710 --> 00:11:24.200
Well those qualities came to
fruition in 1929 with the invention

00:11:24.200 --> 00:11:26.780
that made his reputation.

00:11:26.780 --> 00:11:30.580
Lawrence had been recruited to join
the faculty at Berkeley at a time

00:11:30.580 --> 00:11:33.600
when physics itself
was at the crossroads.

00:11:33.600 --> 00:11:36.850
The deporting generation,
scientist like Ernest Rutherford

00:11:36.850 --> 00:11:40.490
and Marie Curie had been
probing the atomic nucleus

00:11:40.490 --> 00:11:42.470
with the tools that
nature gave them.

00:11:42.470 --> 00:11:46.100
The emissions of alpha rays
from radioactive minerals

00:11:46.100 --> 00:11:50.270
like radium husbanded
by the thimble form.

00:11:50.270 --> 00:11:54.560
With those small science tools
that generation had figured

00:11:54.560 --> 00:11:58.120
out the structure of the atom
and they had discovered x-rays,

00:11:58.120 --> 00:12:00.720
radioactivity and the neutron.

00:12:00.720 --> 00:12:05.280 position:56%
But they'd gone about as much as
they could with nature's gift alone.

00:12:05.280 --> 00:12:08.970
To go further they recognize,
science would need probes

00:12:08.970 --> 00:12:12.000
of higher energies to delve
deeper into the nucleus

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:16.330
and this could only be achieved
by applying human ingenuity.

00:12:16.330 --> 00:12:20.100 position:56%
It was Rutherford who threw down the
challenge for the next generation,

00:12:20.100 --> 00:12:24.510
calling for an apparatus that could
deliver 10 million electron volts,

00:12:24.510 --> 00:12:30.280
yet as he said be safely
accommodated in a medium size room.

00:12:30.280 --> 00:12:34.140
Well, scientist all over the world
took up Rutherford's challenge,

00:12:34.140 --> 00:12:37.610
but what they discovered right
of was that, if you try to apply

00:12:37.610 --> 00:12:42.220 position:56%
or load an apparatus with 10 million
volts, what happens is you blow

00:12:42.220 --> 00:12:45.720
up the apparatus so they ended up
with laboratory field with shards

00:12:45.720 --> 00:12:50.870
of glass and metal, think about
trying to fire a mortar shell

00:12:50.870 --> 00:12:54.500
out of a canon with
a cardboard barrel.

00:12:54.500 --> 00:12:58.450
Well, one night in Berkeley,
Lawrence had a brain storm,

00:12:58.450 --> 00:13:02.130
what if you don't apply the voltage
to the apparatus but directly

00:13:02.130 --> 00:13:05.330
onto the projectile that
you're trying to use?

00:13:05.330 --> 00:13:08.710
If you start with the proton
say with the 100 volts,

00:13:08.710 --> 00:13:12.840
and give it a 100 volt jolt, now
you've got a proton with energy

00:13:12.840 --> 00:13:17.870
of 200 volts, another jolt
and 300 and so on and so on.

00:13:17.870 --> 00:13:21.760
But if you do it to a proton
traveling in a straight line say

00:13:21.760 --> 00:13:27.560
through a linear accelerator, it
would have to be more than a mile

00:13:27.560 --> 00:13:31.310
in length to get to your
particle up to the desired energy,

00:13:31.310 --> 00:13:34.130
so it's not exactly fitting and
rested for it's comfortable room.

00:13:34.130 --> 00:13:40.210
Well, so now comes the second
part of Ernest brainstorm.

00:13:40.210 --> 00:13:42.930
He understands that
a particle crossing

00:13:42.930 --> 00:13:46.330
through a magnetic field
will follow a curve path.

00:13:46.330 --> 00:13:49.760
So if he applies the magnetic
field to this particle,

00:13:49.760 --> 00:13:52.650
he can bend his proton
into a circle,

00:13:52.650 --> 00:13:56.680
allowing it to get repeated jolts
from just a single electrode

00:13:56.680 --> 00:14:00.940
and reducing the need to
synchronize the electrode's charge

00:14:00.940 --> 00:14:02.870
and that's the essence
of the cyclotron,

00:14:02.870 --> 00:14:04.860
reduce to its simplest terms.

00:14:04.860 --> 00:14:07.840
After enough revolutions,
you've got a particle

00:14:07.840 --> 00:14:13.000
that now carries a million volts,
10 million, even a 100 million

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:16.380
and all you have to do is aim
it at a target and let it rip.

00:14:16.380 --> 00:14:21.630 position:56%
The possibilities are limitless and
it all can fit in a medium size room

00:14:21.630 --> 00:14:24.770
or at least the first
cyclotrons could.

00:14:24.770 --> 00:14:28.050
And here's a schematic of
that principle as it appeared

00:14:28.050 --> 00:14:32.150
in Lawrence's patent
application for the accelerator.

00:14:32.150 --> 00:14:35.150
You can see at the center here,

00:14:35.150 --> 00:14:42.360
this is where a charged particle
was introduced to this vacuum tank.

00:14:42.360 --> 00:14:47.230
It spirals through the magnetic
field and at each of these gaps,

00:14:47.230 --> 00:14:52.030
it gets a jolt of energy
until it has enough energy

00:14:52.030 --> 00:14:56.910
to reach the very edge of the
tank where it can be directed

00:14:56.910 --> 00:14:59.070
through another magnetic field out

00:14:59.070 --> 00:15:02.030
and toward the target
for bombardment.

00:15:02.030 --> 00:15:04.660
Well, Lawrence knows
he's on to something.

00:15:04.660 --> 00:15:08.600 position:56%
The very next day, he's seen
bounding across the Berkeley campus,

00:15:08.600 --> 00:15:11.500
but in the holing friends and
colleagues and declaring I'm going

00:15:11.500 --> 00:15:15.280
to be famous, and so he was.

00:15:15.280 --> 00:15:19.140
Over the next decade, Lawrence's
team, using the cyclotron

00:15:19.140 --> 00:15:23.780
to bombard nuclei, discovered
scores of new isotopes including

00:15:23.780 --> 00:15:28.450 position:56%
for example carbon 14, which we
know of for its use in carbon dating

00:15:28.450 --> 00:15:33.440
and for other biological
investigations.

00:15:33.440 --> 00:15:36.750
Other isotopes became the
foundation of the new science

00:15:36.750 --> 00:15:40.330
of nuclear medicine and
the sources of new cures

00:15:40.330 --> 00:15:45.140
and there were new elements to be
discovered heavier than uranium,

00:15:45.140 --> 00:15:47.800
which has not been seen
in the natural state,

00:15:47.800 --> 00:15:51.470
like element 94 plutonium.

00:15:51.470 --> 00:15:55.500
Every discovery made by the
cyclotron opened new business

00:15:55.500 --> 00:15:58.020
and raise new questions
which hadn't--

00:15:58.020 --> 00:16:02.570
and Lawrence responded by designing
new cyclotrons, each one bigger

00:16:02.570 --> 00:16:07.440
and more powerful and more
expensive than the last.

00:16:07.440 --> 00:16:10.290
Big science took shape rapidly.

00:16:10.290 --> 00:16:13.610
In my book, I quote the
physicist Maurice Goldhaber,

00:16:13.610 --> 00:16:17.800
who's career expand the transition
from small science to big science

00:16:17.800 --> 00:16:20.750
and he recalled as he
put it that the first man

00:16:20.750 --> 00:16:23.920
to disintegrate a nucleus
was Ernest Rutherford

00:16:23.920 --> 00:16:27.760
and he could hold the
apparatus in his lap.

00:16:27.760 --> 00:16:31.720 position:56%
Then he said "I remember the
picture of all the scientist sitting

00:16:31.720 --> 00:16:35.600
in the cyclotron's lap and that
gives you an idea of the change."

00:16:35.600 --> 00:16:41.580
And yes, here's Ernest
Rutherford in his lab,

00:16:41.580 --> 00:16:44.330
perhaps not holding his
apparatus in his lab,

00:16:44.330 --> 00:16:45.750
but you can see it all arrange

00:16:45.750 --> 00:16:49.480
on a rather cluttered
laboratory table next to him.

00:16:49.480 --> 00:16:54.730
And here's that picture of the
cyclotron that Goldhaber remembers.

00:16:54.730 --> 00:16:59.280 position:56%
Twenty seven scientist of Lawrence's
radiation lab in Berkeley sitting

00:16:59.280 --> 00:17:04.140
in inside the magnet of
their new 60-inch cyclotron.

00:17:04.140 --> 00:17:08.730
Remarkably, there are three
Nobel Laureates in this picture.

00:17:08.730 --> 00:17:13.060
Let's see there is Luis
Alvarez, right here.

00:17:13.060 --> 00:17:16.270
Ed McMillan is over here.

00:17:16.270 --> 00:17:18.440
I think that's-- I've got McMillan

00:17:18.440 --> 00:17:22.280
who was not only Lawrence's
successor as head of his lab

00:17:22.280 --> 00:17:25.090
but also his brother
in law and, of course,

00:17:25.090 --> 00:17:29.080
Ernest Lawrence is right here in
the middle and one more scientist

00:17:29.080 --> 00:17:32.080
who perhaps stands as the
most accomplished physicist,

00:17:32.080 --> 00:17:34.270
never to get the Nobel Prize

00:17:34.270 --> 00:17:38.540
and that's J. Robert
Oppenheimer who was right up here.

00:17:38.540 --> 00:17:44.280
Well, in 1939, Lawrence won the
Nobel Prize for the cyclotron

00:17:44.280 --> 00:17:47.370
and what was really
notable about the award was

00:17:47.370 --> 00:17:50.490
that for the first time, the
Nobel committee recognized

00:17:50.490 --> 00:17:55.380
that the technique of scientific
investigation had become equally

00:17:55.380 --> 00:18:00.070
important as-- or perhaps even
more important than theory alone.

00:18:00.070 --> 00:18:04.830 position:56%
And Lawrence demonstrated not merely
inspired scientific technique,

00:18:04.830 --> 00:18:07.640
but a genius for scientific
management.

00:18:07.640 --> 00:18:10.610
He showed that when you needed
to raise millions of dollars

00:18:10.610 --> 00:18:14.300
to build your apparatus,
you had to show the genius

00:18:14.300 --> 00:18:18.190
of an entrepreneur,
a general, a CEO.

00:18:18.190 --> 00:18:21.990
You had to find ways to raise
money from university presidents,

00:18:21.990 --> 00:18:26.550
foundation boards, industrial
executives and government officials

00:18:26.550 --> 00:18:29.300
and for scientist,
this was a new religion

00:18:29.300 --> 00:18:31.680
and Ernest Lawrence was to profit.

00:18:31.680 --> 00:18:38.810
Well, the 1939 Nobels were the last
to be awarded until the war clouds

00:18:38.810 --> 00:18:42.740
over Europe began to
dissipate four years later

00:18:42.740 --> 00:18:45.090
and that brings us I
think to the central event

00:18:45.090 --> 00:18:47.350
in Ernest Lawrence's career.

00:18:47.350 --> 00:18:52.220
The Manhattan project will
validate the big science paradigm.

00:18:52.220 --> 00:18:55.210
The atomic bomb could
never have been invented

00:18:55.210 --> 00:18:58.000
by a solitary physicist working

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:01.630
in his solitary lab using
hand made equipment.

00:19:01.630 --> 00:19:04.980
It required an investment
of billions of dollars,

00:19:04.980 --> 00:19:08.200 position:56%
armies of scientist and technicians.

00:19:08.200 --> 00:19:11.800
Laboratories build on
an industrial scale.

00:19:11.800 --> 00:19:15.570
The Manhattan project was the
first great big science program

00:19:15.570 --> 00:19:18.540
and it proved how powerful
an approach this could be

00:19:18.540 --> 00:19:22.180
when it brought together a
large team, in that case more

00:19:22.180 --> 00:19:26.560
than 10,000 scientists
pursuing a shared goal.

00:19:26.560 --> 00:19:30.440
Now, many of, you know, doubt know
at least the outlines of the making

00:19:30.440 --> 00:19:33.030
of the atomic bomb,
the efforts starting

00:19:33.030 --> 00:19:36.350
with Albert Einstein's famous
letter to Franklin Roosevelt

00:19:36.350 --> 00:19:41.170 position:56%
in August 1939, actually the letter
written by the physicist Leo Szilard

00:19:41.170 --> 00:19:43.990
and signed by Albert Einstein.

00:19:43.990 --> 00:19:47.430 position:56%
Observing that the recent
discovery of nuclear fission implied

00:19:47.430 --> 00:19:52.020 position:56%
that bombs could be constructed
from fissionable uranium and warning

00:19:52.020 --> 00:19:56.620
that Nazi Germany might already
be working on the problem.

00:19:56.620 --> 00:19:59.790
The US government swung into
action creating a high level

00:19:59.790 --> 00:20:03.750
of uranium committee to
investigate the possibility.

00:20:03.750 --> 00:20:06.960
But almost immediately, the
effort became bogged down

00:20:06.960 --> 00:20:09.690
and bureaucracy and inertia.

00:20:09.690 --> 00:20:13.240 position:56%
By mid 1941, the two men responsible

00:20:13.240 --> 00:20:17.840
from marshaling America's
scientific manpower and resources

00:20:17.840 --> 00:20:21.390
for the coming war, Vannevar
Bush of the Carnegie Institution

00:20:21.390 --> 00:20:24.040
and James Conant of
Harvard were on the verge

00:20:24.040 --> 00:20:27.920
of cancelling the uranium
bomb project altogether.

00:20:27.920 --> 00:20:30.240 position:56%
And the reasons were understandable.

00:20:30.240 --> 00:20:33.040
Physicists in America
haven't made the case

00:20:33.040 --> 00:20:37.350
that a bomb could be developed in
time to help win the coming war.

00:20:37.350 --> 00:20:40.560
And if that was so, then
every dime spent on a project

00:20:40.560 --> 00:20:43.840
like that would be a dime wasted
because it would be diverted

00:20:43.840 --> 00:20:47.410
from the effort necessary
to win the war.

00:20:47.410 --> 00:20:52.450 position:56%
But then it fell to Lawrence himself
to interpose his personal reputation

00:20:52.450 --> 00:20:55.020 position:56%
in front of the young men, convinced

00:20:55.020 --> 00:20:58.380
that cancellation would be a
short sided and dangerous step,

00:20:58.380 --> 00:21:00.680
he demanded a face-to-face
meeting with Conant.

00:21:00.680 --> 00:21:04.060
And for the first time, James
Conant heard a physicist

00:21:04.060 --> 00:21:08.480
of undisputed stature explain not
only that the bomb was feasible

00:21:08.480 --> 00:21:11.350
in the short term,
but it was urgent.

00:21:11.350 --> 00:21:14.900
The opinion of the physics
community, Lawrence explained,

00:21:14.900 --> 00:21:18.420
especially among those who had
fled Germany and Austria and come

00:21:18.420 --> 00:21:23.570
to the US and the UK was that the
scientists who had stayed behind

00:21:23.570 --> 00:21:24.870
in the Third Reich, people

00:21:24.870 --> 00:21:29.630
like Werner Heinsenberg were
intellectually more than capable

00:21:29.630 --> 00:21:31.610
of designing efficient
bomb themselves.

00:21:31.610 --> 00:21:36.320
And as Lawrence told Conant, if the
Nazi succeed first, they will have

00:21:36.320 --> 00:21:39.240
in their hands the
control of the world.

00:21:39.240 --> 00:21:43.470
Well Conant listened and
he was sort of convinced

00:21:43.470 --> 00:21:45.590
but one thing still bothering him.

00:21:45.590 --> 00:21:48.840
"If only you scientist are so
sure that a bomb is feasible

00:21:48.840 --> 00:21:51.960
and necessary", he said, "How
come none of you has volunteered

00:21:51.960 --> 00:21:54.460
to step ahead and take
over the building of it."

00:21:54.460 --> 00:21:57.820
Ernest he said, "Are you ready
to devote the next few years

00:21:57.820 --> 00:22:00.680
of your life for getting
these bombs made?"

00:22:00.680 --> 00:22:05.230
While Lawrence sort of swallowed
hard and he said, well "Jim,

00:22:05.230 --> 00:22:08.340
if you tell me this is
my job, I will do it."

00:22:08.340 --> 00:22:12.020
And that right there that
saved the atomic bomb program

00:22:12.020 --> 00:22:15.780
and what may be the single
most important meeting

00:22:15.780 --> 00:22:19.950
of the nuclear age, with Ernest
Lawrence's reputation behind it

00:22:19.950 --> 00:22:21.740
and its personal commitment,

00:22:21.740 --> 00:22:25.200
what was soon up the Manhattan
project would never again be

00:22:25.200 --> 00:22:26.740
in doubt.

00:22:26.740 --> 00:22:29.220
Now, I want to show you
one more photograph,

00:22:29.220 --> 00:22:32.720
a very famous historical artifact.

00:22:32.720 --> 00:22:37.880 position:56%
This picture was taken in Lawrence's
office in LeConte Hall in 1940

00:22:37.880 --> 00:22:39.880
at Berkeley and it
shows the brain trust

00:22:39.880 --> 00:22:43.030
of American science
just before the war.

00:22:43.030 --> 00:22:45.480
From the left, there's
Lawrence and then next to him,

00:22:45.480 --> 00:22:49.760
Arthur Holly Compton another Nobel
Laureate and the future transfer

00:22:49.760 --> 00:22:52.310
of Washington University
in Saint Louis.

00:22:52.310 --> 00:22:54.510
Vannevar Bush is next to him.

00:22:54.510 --> 00:22:59.700
There in front is Conant, just
behind him is Carl Compton,

00:22:59.700 --> 00:23:02.950
Arthur's brother and then the
president of MIT and they're

00:23:02.950 --> 00:23:07.310
over on the right, a mysterious
figure named Alfred Loomis

00:23:07.310 --> 00:23:11.230
who had used the millions he
had made as a Wall Street trader

00:23:11.230 --> 00:23:16.100
to build a private physics lab at
his state in Tuxedo Park, New York,

00:23:16.100 --> 00:23:20.010
from which he cultivated and funded
many distinguished young physicist

00:23:20.010 --> 00:23:22.450
including Lawrence
and who is functioning

00:23:22.450 --> 00:23:26.870
as a key behind the scenes adviser
to Bush and Conant during the war.

00:23:26.870 --> 00:23:30.420
Now these gentlemen had come
to Berkeley as a delegation

00:23:30.420 --> 00:23:32.370
from the Rockefeller Foundation

00:23:32.370 --> 00:23:35.870
because Lawrence had sought a
huge grant from the foundation

00:23:35.870 --> 00:23:41.200
to build his biggest cyclotron yet
and he got it, $1.5 million one

00:23:41.200 --> 00:23:44.300
of the largest grants the
foundation had ever made

00:23:44.300 --> 00:23:46.630
to a single researcher.

00:23:46.630 --> 00:23:50.870 position:56%
But what's especially remarkable and
important about this photograph is

00:23:50.870 --> 00:23:54.710
that this exact group would come
together a year later to act

00:23:54.710 --> 00:23:58.940
as a scientific supervisors
of the Manhattan project.

00:23:58.940 --> 00:24:01.180
Well over the following four years,

00:24:01.180 --> 00:24:04.260
Lawrence would play a
paramount role in that program.

00:24:04.260 --> 00:24:07.680
He converted his new
cyclotron into an invention

00:24:07.680 --> 00:24:10.380
to enrich natural uranium
to bomb grade

00:24:10.380 --> 00:24:14.760
by concentrating its
fissionable isotope U-235.

00:24:14.760 --> 00:24:18.860 position:56%
He designed and supervised a
construction of the industrial plant

00:24:18.860 --> 00:24:22.120
to manufacture the enriched
product in a rural district

00:24:22.120 --> 00:24:25.030
in Tennessee known as Oak Ridge.

00:24:25.030 --> 00:24:29.030
That plant would produce every
atom of the uranium for the bomb

00:24:29.030 --> 00:24:31.360
that was dropped at Hiroshima.

00:24:31.360 --> 00:24:33.810
He gave one of his young
associates, the chemist,

00:24:33.810 --> 00:24:38.210
Glenn Seaborg priority time on
its other cyclotrons at Berkeley

00:24:38.210 --> 00:24:40.720
to pursue the isolation
of plutonium,

00:24:40.720 --> 00:24:45.540
which would become the core of
the bomb that destroyed Nagasaki.

00:24:45.540 --> 00:24:49.560
And when General Leslie Groves, the
head of the project came around,

00:24:49.560 --> 00:24:53.130
looking for someone to head up
the actual designing of the bomb

00:24:53.130 --> 00:24:57.940
at the lab that became Los Alamos,
Lawrence nominated his close friend

00:24:57.940 --> 00:25:03.960
and Berkeley colleague, Robert
Oppenheimer, and got him the job.

00:25:03.960 --> 00:25:06.710
Now, all that being said, what
about the moral implications

00:25:06.710 --> 00:25:09.020
of this work not only
Lawrence's role

00:25:09.020 --> 00:25:11.830
but big science's role in the war?

00:25:11.830 --> 00:25:16.170
And, you know, the study of
history is an exercised in looking

00:25:16.170 --> 00:25:18.420
at advance through the eyes
of the people who live them

00:25:18.420 --> 00:25:23.490
but also applying the perspective
of the years or the decades.

00:25:23.490 --> 00:25:27.150
These exercises especially
complicated with nuclear weapons

00:25:27.150 --> 00:25:30.510
because we're so familiar with
the consequences of this work.

00:25:30.510 --> 00:25:33.990
We know the toll in lives
and suffering from Hiroshima

00:25:33.990 --> 00:25:38.250
and Nagasaki, we know the
horrific disfigurements

00:25:38.250 --> 00:25:41.930
and long term illnesses of the
civilian residence of those cities,

00:25:41.930 --> 00:25:43.430
unlike anything experienced

00:25:43.430 --> 00:25:47.300
by any other survivors
of warfare in history.

00:25:47.300 --> 00:25:51.650
We know the cloud that civilization
has lived under for 70 years

00:25:51.650 --> 00:25:54.360 position:56%
because of the decision in the 1940s

00:25:54.360 --> 00:25:58.160
to unleash the distractive
capacity of the nucleus.

00:25:58.160 --> 00:26:01.220
And we know that the Nazis never
actually did have an atomic bomb

00:26:01.220 --> 00:26:05.730
program because the scientists who
stayed behind got the physics wrong

00:26:05.730 --> 00:26:08.490
and concluded it could
never be built.

00:26:08.490 --> 00:26:12.160
But, of course, the allies didn't
know that until the war was over.

00:26:12.160 --> 00:26:17.650
Now Germany surrendered in 1945
changed the calculus of this work

00:26:17.650 --> 00:26:19.900
but not the momentum of the effort.

00:26:19.900 --> 00:26:22.490
But by then, the bombs
were nearly complete.

00:26:22.490 --> 00:26:26.600
The impulse to use them was still
strong, to bring a quick end

00:26:26.600 --> 00:26:30.680
to the war and the final
debate among scientist

00:26:30.680 --> 00:26:33.560
and political leaders
before Hiroshima was

00:26:33.560 --> 00:26:35.100
over whether dropping the bombs

00:26:35.100 --> 00:26:38.630
on the unsuspecting
Japanese was truly necessary

00:26:38.630 --> 00:26:40.230
or whether a demonstration say

00:26:40.230 --> 00:26:44.440
over an unpopulated island would
deliver a sufficiently compelling

00:26:44.440 --> 00:26:47.360
and grim message to
the Japanese regime.

00:26:47.360 --> 00:26:52.520
The record tells us that the last
hold out against dropping the bombs

00:26:52.520 --> 00:26:55.080
on civilians was Lawrence himself,

00:26:55.080 --> 00:26:58.480
but that eventually he too
acknowledged that the risk of it

00:26:58.480 --> 00:27:03.290
that and thus a demonstration that
wouldn't work was too great and he

00:27:03.290 --> 00:27:06.910
and Oppenheimer together signed
the manifesto that was sent

00:27:06.910 --> 00:27:10.970
in Washington, endorsing
the dropping of the bomb.

00:27:10.970 --> 00:27:13.100
Now many of the big scientists

00:27:13.100 --> 00:27:16.140
who developed the atom bomb
including Oppenheimer would soon

00:27:16.140 --> 00:27:18.060
reconsider their role.

00:27:18.060 --> 00:27:21.140
Many would work to promote the
cause of international patrol

00:27:21.140 --> 00:27:23.640 position:56%
over nuclear technology, recognizing

00:27:23.640 --> 00:27:27.380
that what big science had unleashed
could be managed safely only

00:27:27.380 --> 00:27:31.550
through a new conception of
geopolitics and diplomacy.

00:27:31.550 --> 00:27:34.500
Many others would work
to develop nuclear power

00:27:34.500 --> 00:27:37.780
and other peaceful
technologies, perhaps in the hopes

00:27:37.780 --> 00:27:40.740
of expiating the moral
qualms that Hiroshima

00:27:40.740 --> 00:27:43.980
and Nagasaki had brought them to.

00:27:43.980 --> 00:27:47.420
Well, Ernest Lawrence
was not among them.

00:27:47.420 --> 00:27:49.790
Interest fiction was
not his strong suit

00:27:49.790 --> 00:27:53.040
and when he's old friend
Robert Oppenheimer declared

00:27:53.040 --> 00:27:58.140
that through the atomic bomb,
physicists had come to no seen,

00:27:58.140 --> 00:28:01.630
he responded rather
petulantly that nothing

00:28:01.630 --> 00:28:04.820
about his work had
caused him to no seen.

00:28:04.820 --> 00:28:07.280
And that was still
true after the war,

00:28:07.280 --> 00:28:10.570
when he became the nation's
leading scientific promoter

00:28:10.570 --> 00:28:14.820
of the hydrogen bomb, a weapon that
many of his own colleagues viewed

00:28:14.820 --> 00:28:17.430
as nothing but a genocidal device

00:28:17.430 --> 00:28:20.510
and that even the pentagon
acknowledge could never be used

00:28:20.510 --> 00:28:25.740
in a military campaign but
only as a psychological threat.

00:28:25.740 --> 00:28:30.790
But because Ernest died in 1958,
we don't know what he would've made

00:28:30.790 --> 00:28:33.960
of the nuclear world big
science helped create.

00:28:33.960 --> 00:28:37.020
His widow, Molly, thought
he would've been a cast

00:28:37.020 --> 00:28:38.400
at nuclear proliferation.

00:28:38.400 --> 00:28:42.850
In the late 1980s in fact, she
was so appalled at the role

00:28:42.850 --> 00:28:46.540
in the arms race played
by Lawrence's own lab

00:28:46.540 --> 00:28:52.110 position:56%
that she petitioned Congress to take
her husband's name off the facility.

00:28:52.110 --> 00:28:55.100
Well, Congress turned her down
and to this day it's known

00:28:55.100 --> 00:28:59.360
as Lawrence Livermore
National Laboratory.

00:28:59.360 --> 00:29:01.600
But what we can say I think is

00:29:01.600 --> 00:29:05.530
that science itself can't
be seen as good or evil.

00:29:05.530 --> 00:29:10.150
We can only render judgment on
what human that kind makes of it.

00:29:10.150 --> 00:29:12.380
Ernest Lawrence says "New paradigm

00:29:12.380 --> 00:29:16.290
of scientific research has given us
knowledge about the natural world

00:29:16.290 --> 00:29:19.820
that his own contemporaries
could only dream of.

00:29:19.820 --> 00:29:21.310
It's given us isotopes

00:29:21.310 --> 00:29:24.480
and diagnostic techniques
that save lives.

00:29:24.480 --> 00:29:26.240
It put men on the moon.

00:29:26.240 --> 00:29:29.550
It's given us new knowledge
about our own biology.

00:29:29.550 --> 00:29:33.490
It provides us with waste to battle
disease and it may provide us

00:29:33.490 --> 00:29:37.630
with weapons against climate change
even as it's given us the tools

00:29:37.630 --> 00:29:39.780
to destroy ourselves too.

00:29:39.780 --> 00:29:44.170
And I'd like to leave you with
one last topic to think about

00:29:44.170 --> 00:29:45.640
and that's whether after 70

00:29:45.640 --> 00:29:48.290
or 80 years we may have
reached the political

00:29:48.290 --> 00:29:51.100
and economic limits of big science.

00:29:51.100 --> 00:29:55.150
The reason that the Large Hadron
Collider is the biggest accelerator

00:29:55.150 --> 00:29:59.640
in the world is that the United
States abandoned its own parallel

00:29:59.640 --> 00:30:05.440
project, the super conducting,
super collider in the 1990s mostly

00:30:05.440 --> 00:30:07.560
because its budget
had grown so huge,

00:30:07.560 --> 00:30:12.940
but also because the scientific
community itself was not united

00:30:12.940 --> 00:30:14.670
behind it.

00:30:14.670 --> 00:30:16.530 position:56%
Almost since the beginning, the cost

00:30:16.530 --> 00:30:18.450
of big science has
prompted its critics

00:30:18.450 --> 00:30:22.160
to ask whether it can get too
expensive, whether it leads us

00:30:22.160 --> 00:30:26.070
to value, monumental scientific
efforts more than programs

00:30:26.070 --> 00:30:29.130
that might have a direct
relevance to our daily lives

00:30:29.130 --> 00:30:32.100
like ending poverty or hunger.

00:30:32.100 --> 00:30:35.500
Big science has helped
make our universities great

00:30:35.500 --> 00:30:39.690
but it's also helped turn our
professors into administrators,

00:30:39.690 --> 00:30:45.210
housekeepers and publicists all
for the cause of raising more money

00:30:45.210 --> 00:30:47.670
to make science even bigger.

00:30:47.670 --> 00:30:51.640
And part of that, I think it's
the political fear it inspires

00:30:51.640 --> 00:30:55.970
