be concerned about sort of the--

00:44:59.260 --> 00:45:01.940
I guess the commercialization
of early stage science

00:45:01.940 --> 00:45:07.230
that we're seeing in places like
Silicon Valley and elsewhere.

00:45:07.230 --> 00:45:13.730
We certainly have seen cases where
scientist working on basic science

00:45:13.730 --> 00:45:19.140
at publicly funded institutions
end up sort of hiding their work

00:45:19.140 --> 00:45:23.360 position:56%
from colleagues because they can
see some commercial potential in it.

00:45:23.360 --> 00:45:28.110
Laurence himself was very
skeptical about patenting even.

00:45:28.110 --> 00:45:31.680
And this was a skepticism
that was much more common

00:45:31.680 --> 00:45:33.600
in his day than it is now.

00:45:33.600 --> 00:45:36.360
He resisted patenting
the cyclotron originally

00:45:36.360 --> 00:45:40.180
but he himself had patrons who
said, look, you have to protect,

00:45:40.180 --> 00:45:42.880
you have to protect your invention

00:45:42.880 --> 00:45:45.980
from commercial exploitation
that you can't control.

00:45:45.980 --> 00:45:49.770
So they insisted that he
file a patent and he did.

00:45:49.770 --> 00:45:51.660
Reluctantly he didn't
like the process.

00:45:51.660 --> 00:45:55.580
He didn't like having to explain
his work through patent examiners

00:45:55.580 --> 00:45:56.880
who couldn't understand it.

00:45:56.880 --> 00:46:01.310
Later in his career, he was under
pressure to patent the isotopes

00:46:01.310 --> 00:46:03.040
that we're coming out of his lab.

00:46:03.040 --> 00:46:06.380
He resisted that and
he won that battle.

00:46:06.380 --> 00:46:10.770
In part, he won it by default
because the patent examiners

00:46:10.770 --> 00:46:16.090
of the day couldn't be convinced
that that the creation of isotopes

00:46:16.090 --> 00:46:19.880
which were natural
materials could actually be

00:46:19.880 --> 00:46:23.380
that this could be
patentable inventions

00:46:23.380 --> 00:46:25.030
but he didn't like the idea.

00:46:25.030 --> 00:46:26.420
He didn't like it originally.

00:46:26.420 --> 00:46:30.360
He didn't like the encouraging
of that sort of commercialism

00:46:30.360 --> 00:46:32.410
and politics into his lab.

00:46:32.410 --> 00:46:36.760 position:56%
But I think this was a tide that he
tried to hide back and he wasn't all

00:46:36.760 --> 00:46:39.120
that successful in doing.

00:46:39.120 --> 00:46:41.590
So-- And so I think that's it.

